{ Welcome to the course! Here I analyze three annoying openings that a 1.d4 player will often encounter  (particularly)  in faster time controls. These are the English Defense and it's two 'cousins', the Accelerated Queen's Indian Defense  (QID)  and Owen's Defense. The coverage of the latter is also useful for 1.e4 players.  Despite them not having a good reputation, these sidelines are quite tricky and White has to be well prepared to emerge with an advantage out of the opening. The good news is they fail to equalize so if you learn the lines in this course, you will have an advantage  (oftentimes a big or even a decisive one)  !  I decided to make this small course FREE as a way of giving back to the wonderful Chessable community with which I've had a great time and learned a lot from.  Finally, if you have any questions  (or even better find improvements for White or Black)  don't hesitate to post in the forums.  I hope you enjoy this course and score a lot of points with it! }
1. d4
{ Owen's defense from the perspective of a  1.e4  player is covered inchapter 5. }
1... e6
{ 1...Nf6  2.c4  b6  The Accelerated Queen's Indian Defense @@StartBracket@@QID@@EndBracket@@ is tackled inchapter 3.   1...b6  Owen's Defense, a 'cousin' of the English Defense, is analyzed in chapter 4. }
2. c4 b6 { The English Defense is covered inchapter 2. } *

