{ The English defense. Contrary to the English opening @@StartBracket@@1. c4@@EndBracket@@, this defense is not very good. However, it is quite tricky and White needs to know a few lines to get an advantage. }
3. e4 { No reason not to create a big pawn center. } 3... Bb7 4. Bd3
{ Protecting the pawn on e4 with the bishop is the way to go. We don't want to play Nc3 right away to avoid the pin after ...Bb4. }
4... Bb4+ 5. Kf1
{ Simple and strong. White has a big space advantage and should thus not trade pieces with moves like Bd2. The king on f1 will be perfectly safe and it also defends the g2 pawn, which nullifies Black's typical ...f5 pawn break. Finally, White will often push h4-h5, when the Rh1 can be lifted to h3. }
5... Be7 { We will now develop sensibly with Nc3, Nf3 and Qe2. } 6. Nc3 d6 7.
Nf3 Nd7 8. Qe2 { Centralizing the queen and overprotecting the e4 pawn. } 8...
Ngf6
{ The alternative development scheme with  8...Bf6  can be met with  9.h4  Ne7  10.Bc2  O-O  11.Bg5  Nc6  12.Rd1⩲ }
9. h4
{ White has a clear advantage thanks to the control over the center and the extra space it affords. Note how Black's pieces are confined to the last three ranks of the board. We can continue with moves like h5, Bf4  (preparing a potential e5 break)  , and even Rh3-g3 in certain variations. }
