{ The English defense. Contrary to the English opening @@StartBracket@@1. c4@@EndBracket@@, this defense is not very good. However, it is quite tricky and White needs to know a few lines to get an advantage. }
3. e4 { No reason not to create a big pawn center. } 3... Bb7 4. Bd3
{ Protecting the pawn on e4 with the bishop is the way to go. We don't want to play Nc3 right away to avoid the pin after ...Bb4. }
4... Nc6
{ Black wants to go after the d3 bishop with Nb4. This variation was recommended by both GM Dejan Bojkov and GM Nigel Davies in two separate chessbase DVDs. }
5. Ne2
{ The knight is best placed on e2, retaining the flexibility of later reinforcing the center with f3 or even pushing ahead with f4. }
5... Nb4
{ 5...g6  was played by Alireza Firouzja in 2018 but is not particularly good.  6.Nbc3  Bg7  7.Be3  Nge7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Rc1  is a logical sequence of moves, when White stands clearly better thanks to the excellent control over the center. }
6. O-O
{ Surprisingly, GM Nigel Davies in his ChessBase DVD 'Original and aggressive 1...b6 for practical players' did not consider this natural developing move. }
6... Nxd3 7. Qxd3 { Black captured the bishop but wasted a lot of time. } 7...
Ne7
{ The alternative developing scheme with   7...d6  8.Nbc3  Nf6  leads to very similar play as the mainline after  9.d5  e5  10.f4± }
8. Nbc3 d6 9. d5
{ Under the right circumstances, we can open this position with f4-f5. White has more space in the center and is already fully developed. On the other hand, Black is way behind in development and his pieces are very passive.   9...Qd7  10.a4  a5  11.Nb5  g6  was seen in Kramnik, Vladimir  (2759)  vs Ponomariov, Ruslan  (2727)  in 2009. We can improve on the game with  12.Be3!  setting the following devious trap  12...Bg7?  13.dxe6  fxe6  14.Bxb6!  cxb6  15.Nxd6  Kf8  16.Qf3+  with a winning attack. }
