{ Black hasn't proven any compensation for White's pawn center. } 6... d6 7.
O-O
{ Surprisingly, GM Nigel Davies in his ChessBase DVD 'Original and aggressive: 1...b6 for practical players' did not consider this natural move. He only looked at the immediate d5, after which he suggested fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop. }
7... Be7
{ Fianchettoing the bishop with   7...g6  is strongly met by  8.Bb5  White is now threatening Qc4 and d5, winning the knight on c6. Thus, Black is practically forced to play  8...Nd7  but this loses a pawn by force after the following forced sequence of moves  9.Bg5  Be7  10.Bxe7  Qxe7  11.Qc4  Threatening to capture the knight on c6.  11...Na5  12.Qxc7  Rc8  13.Qxd7+  Qxd7  14.Bxd7+  Kxd7  15.Nbd2  +-  White has an extra pawn and thus a decisive advantage. Black has no compensation. }
8. d5 { It's time to push Black's pieces back } 8... Nb8 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 Nbd7
11. Be3 a5 12. Nd2
{ We have completed our development and have a clear advantage. This position is sort of a King's Indian gone completely wrong for Black. The light-squared bishop is completely misplaced on b7 and the standard ...f5 break @@StartBracket@@Black's only source of counterplay in the King's Indian@@EndBracket@@ is impossible here. White can play on both sides of the board, either with Bc2+a3+b4 or on the kingside with the g3+f4 break. }
